---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import AdSlot from '../../components/AdSlot.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Getting Started Guide — New to Rise of Kingdoms"
  description="A guide for new Rise of Kingdoms players covering civilization choice, building priority, attack strategy, and alliance advice."
  lang="en"
  alternatePath="/baslangic-rehberi"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold text-foreground sm:text-4xl">Getting Started Guide</h1>
    <p class="mt-3 text-muted">
      If you're new to Rise of Kingdoms, the decisions you make in the first few days determine your kingdom's
      long-term strength. The four core principles below give you a solid start, especially if you're playing free
      to play (F2P).
    </p>

    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-headings:font-display prose-headings:text-accent-purple-light mt-10 max-w-none">
      <h2>1. Choosing a Civilization</h2>
      <p>
        There's no single "correct" civilization — it depends on your playstyle, not your budget. That said, there's
        a clear default for new players, and later on the right pick depends on which troop type you're building
        around and what role you play in KvK.
      </p>

      <h3>For F2P Players</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>China</strong> (recommended starting pick) — provides +5% building speed and +5% action point
          recovery, exactly the two bonuses that matter most when you can't buy speedups, since they keep your
          build queue moving. You also get Sun Tzu for free, one of the strongest Epic commanders in the game.
          Once your Town Hall reaches around level 25, construction stops being your bottleneck, and that's the
          point to switch civilizations (a free civilization change is already available).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Spain</strong> (a solid next step after China) — its +20% resource production is a passive bonus
          that keeps working without spending action points on gathering, exactly the kind of "always-on" advantage
          that matters most for F2P accounts.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>For Low Spenders</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Britain</strong> — if you're active in alliance fort or pass defense, its +20% allied garrison
          capacity pays off directly.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Rome</strong> — if you're leaning defensive while still caring about your economy, infantry
          defense plus food gathering speed strikes a good balance.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>For End-Game / KvK Players</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Korea</strong> (when you're heading into a T5 troop unlock or a months-long research push like
          Crystal Technology) — its +3% research speed adds up fast over long research chains, and +15% hospital
          capacity makes it much easier to treat the heavy losses KvK produces.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>France</strong> (if you're fighting with an infantry-heavy army) — +20% hospital healing speed,
          the highest in the game, gets your troops back into the fight far faster after a battle.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Arabia</strong> (if you're a rally leader built around cavalry) — cavalry attack and rallied army
          damage bonuses translate directly into rally damage.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Ottoman Empire</strong> (if your commanders are built around skill damage) — +5% commander skill
          damage is a bonus you won't find on most other civilizations.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>2. Prioritize the Town Hall</h2>
      <p>
        The maximum level of almost every building in your city is tied to your Town Hall level. That's why you
        should always prioritize upgrading the Town Hall before spending resources elsewhere. As your Town Hall
        level rises, you unlock the ability to upgrade other buildings, technologies, and troop capacity — so your
        early-game focus needs to be clear.
      </p>

      <h2>3. Don't Attack Other Players' Cities</h2>
      <p>
        Attacking other players' cities in the early game creates unnecessary hostility and puts your troops and
        resources at risk. Instead, target barbarians and barbarian forts on the map to gain experience and gather
        resources safely. Once Kingdoms vs. Kingdoms (KvK) eras arrive, there will be plenty of opportunity for
        aggressive play.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Join an Active Alliance</h2>
      <p>
        An active, cooperative alliance is one of the most important sources of security and growth in the game.
        Help sent by alliance members significantly shortens construction and research times, alliance
        technologies grant extra bonuses to your city, and a strong alliance protects you from enemy attacks. When
        choosing an alliance, pay attention to daily active member counts and how helpful the leadership is.
      </p>
    </article>

    <div class="mt-12">
      <AdSlot label="Advertisement" />
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
